<h1>Pitch initialization</h1>

<p>
Abjad provides four different ways to initialize <code>Pitch</code> objects.
</p>

<!--
<ul>
   <li> by integer
   <li> by float
   <li> by name, octave
   <li> by pitch-class, number
</ul>
-->

<h2>By integer</h2>

<p>
The usual way to instantiate <code>Pitch</code> objects is with integers.
</p>

<pre>
  abjad> Pitch(-10)
  Pitch(d, 3)
</pre>

<pre>
  abjad> Pitch(23)
  Pitch(b, 4)
</pre>

<h2>By float</h2>

<p>
For quartertones, you can initialize <code>Pitch</code> with floats.
</p>

<pre>
  abjad> Pitch(12.0)
  Pitch(c, 5)
</pre>

<pre>
  abjad> Pitch(12.5)
  Pitch(cqs, 5)
</pre>

<h2>By name, octave</h2>

<p>
Initalize <code>Pitch</code> with pitchclass and octave to specify accidentals explicitly.
</p>

<pre>
   abjad> Pitch('cs', 4)
   Pitch(cs, 4)
</pre>

<pre>
   abjad> Pitch('df', 4)
   Pitch(df, 4)
</pre>


<h2>By number, letter</h2>

<p>
Abjad will supply the correct accidental for a pitch of a given number if you supply the pitch letter against which to notate.
</p>

<pre>
   abjad> Pitch(13, 'c')
   Pitch(cs, 5)
</pre>

<pre>
   abjad> Pitch(13, 'd')
   Pitch(df, 5)
</pre>

<h2 class="end-of-page">Comments</h2>

<p class="comment">
Abjad implements the initialization schemes documented here as a collection of <strong>initializers</strong>.
</p>

<p>
Initializers are private classes that initialize Abjad classes and do nothing else.
</p>

<p>
Abjad pitch initializers live in <code>pitch/initializers.py</code>. Add new pitch initializers there.
</p>

<p class="comment">
Abjad allows empty pitch initialization with <code>Pitch( )</code>.
Future implementations of Abjad may deprecate this behavior.
</p>
